english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Passage
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There is a man called Yang Saeng, whom all recognize as a person of true understanding, and he has built his dwelling north of the city. Skilled in grafting and nurturing flowers and trees, his garden has earned a fine reputation even in the capital. I went to see it myself, and found only bare walls enclosing an empty space—at first there seemed nothing remarkable, nothing to match what I had heard. Only when the master led me into his garden did I turn my gaze about, searching for the source of its fame. The garden spans but forty paces, yet within it precious trees and rare fruits stand in careful rows, neither crowding one another nor standing so far apart as to seem scattered. All is arranged with perfect measure and spacing by Yang Saeng's own hand.

    Separate from this, he has made a garden bed for flowers—dozens of varieties, flowers rarely seen in this world. Some were opening just then, others already fallen, painting the forest and embroidering the earth in tangled profusion. The crimson buds bright in the sun recall the charming intoxication of Zhang Li-hua. The petals wet with dew are like Yang Gui-fei just emerging from her bath. The branches swaying in the wind move with the lightness of Zhao Fei-yan's form. Those that have fallen are like Shen Fu-ren yielding her seat, while those still closed are like Lady Li drawing the coverlet over herself. So does the garden speak through flowers to the eye that I could not bear to leave, but sat long upon the grass before rising.

    From the flower terrace, going a little north, there stands a stone platform, level as a go-board and so clean one may sit upon it without a mat. Below, grape vines trail down like a jeweled necklace—charming beyond measure. Beneath lies a stone well of water perfectly clear and sweet. It seeps out to form a small pool where young reeds begin to grow. I remarked that if one raised the rim somewhat higher to gather more water, it could become a pond for ducks.

    Returning to the stone platform, we passed the wine cup several times. The master looked at me and said, "Though I possess this hall, I have never inscribed it with characters. Have I not been waiting for you? Might I trouble you to give it a name?" And so I named it the Hall of Passage.

    When one follows the Way to perceive all things in silence, the distinction between passage and obstruction becomes impossible to see. Yet in terms of Heaven's Way, the sun and moon, the stars, mountains and rivers—these are the greatest of all things, and yet none escape the cycles of fullness and emptiness, flourishing and decline, opening and closing. This is because nothing escapes the mathematics of yin and yang. How much less so all other things?

    A place may be open, yet if obstructed by people, mist brings melancholy and moonlight brings sorrow—it never becomes a place of true passage. A person may become one who truly understands, yet if blocked by circumstance, even the wisest and most talented turn their heads northward and never arrive. Who then would know such a person existed?

    But this hall—here the place is open and the man of understanding dwells within it. How can it not be called the Hall of Passage? Though one might wish to decline such a name, how can one escape it? Heaven and earth show no favoritism—why should they alone favor Yang Saeng with springs and stones, with flowers and willows? It comes simply from the subtlety of the craftsman's mind. Thus the blooming flowers and fragrant grasses are not gifts from Heaven, but from Yang Saeng's hands. The jade well and clear spring are not products of the earth, but products of Yang Saeng's heart.

    Alas, I do not know what this place was before. Perhaps the land was barren, the garden common, grasses wild and trees ancient, with ten thousand vistas hidden and unexpressed. Only when Yang Saeng arrived did it become like a fairy's dwelling place! Should he have abandoned it or passed it to another, would it not have become merely a pig-trough and a horse-stall?

    Since Yang Saeng has asked me to write this record, I set down what my eyes have witnessed. Yang Saeng greatly admires the spirit of chivalry and delights in helping others in their need—he is indeed a man with whom one cannot but spend one's time.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhang Li-hua was a renowned beauty favored by the last emperor of the Southern Chen during China's period of division, celebrated for her charming grace.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhao Fei-yan was a beloved concubine of the Han emperor, famous for her lightness—it was said she could dance upon the palm of a man's hand.
  - key: ''
    value: Lady Shen was loved by the Han emperor Wen, and when she once sat beside the empress in the palace garden, a man named Yuan-ang respectfully yielded his seat to her.
  - key: ''
    value: Lady Li was beloved by the Han emperor Wu. When she died, the emperor wished to see her face one last time, but she kept her countenance covered with the bedding, refusing to be seen even in death.
